1_0	0.0	CHANGSHA, March 22 (Xinhua) --Spiders once were considered disgusting for their dangerous, ugly appearance.
1_1	0.07142857142857142	However, for local paddy growers in the Dongting Lake area in central China, spiders have become their best friends for killing pests.
1_2	0.0	Some paddy land has been idle to set up safety for spiders.
1_3	0.0	"If the spiders can pass the winter safely, the pests will not be a threat to the crops," says a local farmer.
1_4	0.0	Chinese books written 2,000 years ago read, "All are happy when spiders are flourishing".
1_5	0.3333333333333333	A spider eats five-to-six insect pests every day, a local expert says.
1_6	0.625	The lake area is the first in China to study pest control with spiders.
1_7	0.0	Many local villages have benefited ecologically.
1_8	0.0	"The area used to be plagued by pests," recalls Liu Hui, a local expert in Xiangyin County, Hunan Province, "and chemicals had been used as the only weapon to fight them".
1_9	0.0	The amount of chemicals used was drastically reduced after spiders were introduced, which has resulted in better quality of farm products, according to the expert.
1_10	0.0	According to local officials, the natural technology has become popular in the area and is expected to be adopted by farmers in other parts of the country.
1_11	0.0	Nevertheless, local people want to gain something from their invention.
1_12	0.0	Xiangyin County plans to turn its vast spider-guarded farmlands into a new destination for tourists, and a school for outside farmers who are eager to learn the cost-effective natural technology.
2_0	0.0	One of the best things to happen to salads in decades is that zippy Italian green called arugula.
2_1	0.23076923076923078	It's literally a weed in Italy, and it would grow just as easily in anybody's garden if not for one tiny problem: the flea beetle.
2_2	0.1875	Flea beetles are minuscule black insects that appear early in the spring and spend the rest of the season leaping among the plants, chewing holes in leaves.
2_3	0.0	They hop like fleas, hence the common name.
2_4	0.0	If there are enough of them, they can nibble seedlings to the ground.
2_5	0.75	Actually, there are several species of flea beetles.
2_6	0.15384615384615385	Some prefer nightshade family plants like eggplant and tomatoes, and some prefer cabbage family plants like broccoli and arugula.
2_7	0.0	In my garden, the cabbage-eaters are more numerous, and they adore arugula.
2_8	0.05	If I sow arugula seeds in early spring, to take advantage of the cool weather they like, I have to swathe the spot in one of those diaphanous row covers immediately, before the seeds germinate.
2_9	0.25	If I don't, the flea beetles will chomp the seedlings into oblivion the moment the first leaves peek above the surface.
2_10	0.6	Even so, the flea beetles know the arugula is there.
2_11	0.0	They alight on the protective cover, patiently waiting for me to lift it to snag a bunch of arugula, so they can sneak in and start munching.
2_12	0.0	I imagine saliva dripping from their little jaws.
2_13	0.3076923076923077	It is no comfort to know that this pest is an accidental import, like the European corn borer, the Japanese beetle and the gypsy moth.
