2_15	0.0	They got off the boat in British Columbia and made their way steadily eastward.
2_16	0.2	The North American countryside is rich in cabbage family weeds like yellow rocket and winter cress, and the flea beetles flourished.
2_17	0.0	The tiny terrorists arrived in the Northeast in the 1950s and have spent the last half-century establishing themselves as garden pests, as if anyone needed more of those.
2_18	0.3333333333333333	Several mild winters in a row have made the problem even worse by allowing more flea beetles to survive.
2_19	0.0	What's a gardener to do?
2_20	0.47368421052631576	At a conference in New Haven this winter, research scientists and organic farmers pondered the perplexing problem of Phyllotreta cruciferae, the cabbage-crunching flea beetle, as well as its nightshade-noshing cousins.
2_21	0.0	Not much research has been done on the agile insects, because they are not a big problem for conventional vegetable growers.
2_22	0.4444444444444444	(Pesticides applied to kill other insects tend to keep flea beetles in check).
2_23	0.0	For organic growers and most backyard gardeners, though, they are tough to control.
2_24	0.0	Like other beetles, they are hard-bodied.
2_25	0.0	They also bound away at the slightest disturbance.
2_26	0.07692307692307693	Those characteristics put them out of reach of most botanical pesticides and even the chemicals commonly available for home use, because the pesticide has to touch the insects to kill them.
2_27	0.3548387096774194	Aside from keeping the beetles' favorite foods under cover, farmers reported trying _ with limited success _ to repel them with garlic and hot pepper sprays, planting cabbage family crops among aromatic herbs and vacuuming the insects off their crops with leaf blowers adapted to work in reverse.
2_28	0.2	Some tried to snare the flea beetles on sticky traps: pieces of white or yellow poster board taped to bamboo sticks and coated with a gooey product called Tangle-Trap.
2_29	0.375	Flea beetles are attracted to white and yellow, and they paste themselves to the traps in numbers.
2_30	0.16	Kimberly Stoner, an entomologist at the Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station in New Haven, tried baiting sticky traps with mustard oil, the substance that cabbage-loving flea beetles home in on when they're looking for their favorite snack plants.
2_31	0.0	The baited traps worked, perhaps too well.
2_32	0.0	``I suspect that they attract many more beetles than they trap,'' she said.
2_33	0.0	Those tempted to try this at home should be warned that concentrated mustard oil can make eyes water and burn skin.
2_34	0.21428571428571427	Repellent sprays, traps and covers are usually enough to keep flea beetles from doing fatal damage to crops like broccoli, turnips and rutabagas, but nothing can keep them from making unattractive holes in leafy greens like arugula and mizuna, a mild Japanese mustard that's also splendid in salads.
2_35	0.4444444444444444	For now, there is only one solution to the flea beetle problem: grow the most vulnerable crops in the fall.
