2_40	0.25	A European study found that up to 90 percent of wintering flea beetles of the arugula-munching variety had been killed by beneficial nematodes, tiny soil-dwelling worms.
3_0	0.0	BOSTON (AP) --Who knew sex could be such a powerful weapon against hungry cranberry-eating pests?
3_1	0.0	A new pest-fighting weapon interferes with the moths' mating rituals, resulting in fewer of the dreaded Sparganothis fruitworm.
3_2	0.0	``Moths are going to have to take lots of cold showers,'' said Jeffrey LaFleur, executive director of the Cape Cod Cranberry Growers' Association.
3_3	0.0	With 14,400 acres of bogs, Massachusetts is the second-largest producer of cranberries in the nation, producing 1.8 million barrels a season.
3_4	0.0	Wisconsin produces 2.5 million barrels.
3_5	0.09090909090909091	The fruitworms can be devastating to a cranberry crop, infesting and destroying up to 50 percent of a bog in a bad year.
3_6	0.0	They burrow into the fruit, munching their way from one to the next, rendering the cranberry useless as food or drink.
3_7	0.07142857142857142	The latest antiworm device uses the insect's own pheromones, which control sexual desire, to lead the bug astray.
3_8	0.0	Moths mate around this time of year, producing eggs that turn into the worms that feast on cranberries between late summer and early autumn.
3_9	0.3	Scientists were able to replicate the pheromones released by the female moths to attract males for mating.
3_10	0.1111111111111111	The pheromones have been bottled in liquid form, for all practical reasons an insect perfume.
3_11	0.15384615384615385	The liquid is then mixed into a cranberry bog's irrigation system, sending the moths into a blind sexual tizzy.
3_12	0.0	The males smell the females, but because the scent is everywhere, they can't find the potential partners (unless, of course, they are fortunate enough to bump into one).
3_13	0.0	The result: fewer eggs are laid, and that translates into fewer of the berry-eating worms, said LaFleur, who sounds positively gleeful as he discusses the insect's demise.
3_14	0.0	Where the pheromones leave off, the worms' predators --such as wasps -- take over.
3_15	0.125	LaFleur predicts the fruitworm could disappear from Massachusetts cranberry bogs over several years.
3_16	0.0	This season, a handful of growers are testing out the pheromone on several hundred acres of Massachusetts bogs.
3_17	0.0	The product is nontoxic to other species and to humans, said LaFleur, whose organization represents about 80 percent of the cranberry growers in the state.
