8_6	0.125	In his case, that creativity includes an increasing emphasis on organic farming.
8_7	0.0	Fresno native Jones, 37, came up through the farming ranks.
8_8	0.0	At 16, he was picking melons in Arizona.
8_9	0.0	After that he worked as a trucker and an irrigator, among other jobs, eventually ending up in the Salinas Valley strawberry fields in 1982.
8_10	0.0	``I got hooked on strawberries,'' he says with a laugh.
8_11	0.0	He is also hooked on the valley with its ideal growing conditions created by rich soil and a relatively cool, moderate climate.
8_12	0.0	Several years ago, he and two partners converted eight of their approximately 125 acres of strawberries to organic, and the results were everything they could have hoped for.
8_13	0.0	The berries taste and look great, and there is increasing demand for them.
8_14	0.2	Windward had been moving toward less reliance on chemicals for at least 10 years, reducing pesticide use by as much as 80 percent, Jones says: ``Then we started thinking, if we can control pests organically, why not go all the way?
8_15	0.0	(Using fish emulsion and other non-chemical fertilizers)''.
8_16	0.0	Windward Farming now has 22 acres of organic berries and more acreage in transition.
8_17	0.09090909090909091	It takes three years to convert from conventional to certified organic status, and therein lies a problem.
8_18	0.0	Jones and partners, like many small- to medium-size agricultural enterprises in the area, lease their land, typically on a two-year basis.
8_19	0.0	To go through the conversion process and make it worthwhile, ``we really need six- to eight-years leases,'' he asserts.
8_20	0.0	At the same time, he understands why such leases aren't offered.
8_21	0.0	The land, for the most part, is not owned by large companies but by families with long ties to the area.
8_22	0.0	The land is so valuable that they just cannot tie it up in long-term leases, he admits.
8_23	0.0	At the same time, that value is a certain guarantee against encroaching development.
8_24	0.0	``Last time farmland was for sale here,'' Jones reports somewhat incredulously, ``it went for $30,000 an acre''.
8_25	0.0	Jones' advocacy of organic methods is both philosophical and practical.
8_26	0.5769230769230769	So-called trap crops _ flowers, alfalfa _ planted alongside cash crops attract beneficial insects and simultaneously take care of such nasty critters as the lygus bug, a small insect that winters in the hills and comes down to the valley in spring.
8_27	0.0	The lygus injects a poisonous substance into the seeds on the skin of strawberries, causing the seeds to die and making for misshapen berries.
8_28	0.0	However, given a flavor choice of strawberry or alfalfa, the lygus will go for alfalfa every time, leaving the berries unmolested and proving that organic methods not only make good sense on ecological grounds but are also cost-effective, Jones says.
8_29	0.0	What's more, organically grown berries always win in taste tests, report employees of Driscoll Strawberry Associates, the large shipper that contracts with Jones and many other growers.
8_30	0.0	(Jones also gets his patented plants from Driscoll's nurseries).
8_31	0.0	While organic growing methods are still in their infancy nationwide and account for a relatively small percentage of fruit grown in the Salinas Valley, the idea is catching on.
8_32	0.0	For growers like Jones, the popularity of organic produce means higher prices, which in turn means that field workers receive a better wage _ typically $9.80 an hour rather than the $9.35 working in conventionally cultivated fields _ guaranteeing their commitment to these environment-friendly methods.
8_33	0.0	``Our people (workers) are the real key to our success,'' says Jones, adding proudly that his company experiences a 95 percent return rate among the roughly 150 workers employed during the May-November harvest season.
8_34	0.0	During that time, 16-hour work days are common.
8_35	0.0	Jones admits ruefully that at times he's so bushed that he forgets to bring home berries for his wife and three children for days on end.
8_36	0.0	``But my wife (Ruth Anne) knows how to improve my memory,'' he admits.
