9_1	0.0	As he talks, he picks his supper.
9_2	0.0	``See the holes in the Swiss chard''? he asked.
9_3	0.0	``People don't normally buy it because of the holes.
9_4	0.0	I prefer to eat the holes than the chemicals''.
9_5	0.0	Then he makes a little joke: ``If you are lucky, you get extra protein from the bugs''.
9_6	0.0	In fact, there are very few blemishes on the rows of chard and lettuce, spinach and cabbage, even though chemicals are never sprayed in this three-acre garden.
9_7	0.0	Ceballos' work is guided by one principle: ``In nature, all is in balance, and if you kill part of that balance it damages the environment''.
9_8	0.0	He also applies that belief in cultivating the olive and fruit trees at the resort, and in tending its beehives.
9_9	0.0	In summer, 90 percent to 95 percent of the fruits and vegetables served to Rancho La Puerta's 150 guests have been grown by Ceballos and his staff; in the winter, the proportion drops to 50 percent.
9_10	0.0	Ceballos, 44, a biologist from Tecate with a master's degree in ecology from the National Autonomous University of Mexico, intended to be a wildlife manager.
9_11	0.0	But 14 years ago he was persuaded to work at the ranch by Sarah Livia Brightwood, the daughter of its founders.
9_12	0.5	She wanted to restore the organic garden her father had planted 50 years earlier.
9_13	0.0	``If you talk about healthy living at the ranch, you should be eating healthy food,'' she said.
9_14	0.0	The garden had lain fallow for 25 years, abandoned when a nematode problem overwhelmed the crops.
9_15	0.0	The worms were still there when work began, but new strategies have been developed for dealing with them.
9_16	0.0	For example, a crop of a species of marigold that is a nematode suppressor was planted.
9_17	0.42857142857142855	The marigolds did their job so well that other crops could be planted near them.
9_18	0.0	The area of heaviest nematode infestation is now planted with fruit trees that are resistant to them, and with herbs and flowers the pests aren't interested in.
9_19	0.35294117647058826	Being an organic farmer requires sensitivity, creativity and observation to decide what is planted, and when, where and how; to know such things as which weeds should be left and which pulled, and what companion planting accomplishes.
9_20	0.0	Following are some lessons learned from a stroll in Ceballos' garden.
9_21	1.0833333333333333	_ Flowers are essential in a vegetable garden because they attract beneficial insects like praying mantises and ladybugs, which eat aphids.
9_22	0.25	_ Basil and tomatoes are planted together because the herb repels worms that love the fruit.
9_23	0.35714285714285715	_ Plants in the onion family, like chives or garlic, are planted with broccoli and cabbage because the alliums discourage aphids from feasting on the cruciferous vegetables.
9_24	0.0	_ Plants are placed close to one another, to conserve water.
9_25	0.0	Cabbage is planted with lettuce, which matures first; after the lettuce is picked the cabbage fills in the spaces.
9_26	0.2	_ Spinach that grows in the wild is transplanted to beds of cultivated spinach; the wild spinach is more resistant to bugs and gives the cultivated spinach more of a chance.
9_27	0.0	_ In a form of crop rotation, celery is planted after tomatoes because tomatoes take a lot of nitrogen from the soil and celery needs very little.
9_28	0.0	_ Weeds that are not too aggressive are allowed because their roots help retain moisture in the soil.
9_29	0.0	Ceballos plans to make herbal teas from the new herb garden, and soon there will be eggs from the organic chickens that have just arrived.
9_30	0.0	He also makes about 300 gallons of cold-pressed, unfiltered olive oil from trees in the garden.
9_31	0.0	``This farming is a low-tech activity,'' he said.
9_32	0.0	``It depends so much on the senses, knowing the cycles of the moon, the soil''.
9_33	0.0	Many spa guests spend part of their stay weeding and planting.
9_34	0.0	``Some people who live in apartments never have had the opportunity to feel soil,'' Ceballos said.
9_35	0.0	``They ask me about the trees carrots grow on.''
10_0	0.0	Q: Something is chewing small holes in the leaves of my vegetables.
10_1	0.0	I have looked closely to try to find an insect, and something appears to hop away when I move the leaves.
10_2	0.0	Any clue as to what this is?
10_3	0.15	A: Flea beetles are minuscule insects _ adults are about 1/16 inch long and black or greenish-black _ that appear in spring and leap among plants and chew numerous, small holes in leaves.
10_4	0.0	They hop like fleas, therefore their common name.
10_5	0.0	If there are enough of them, they can do considerable damage.
10_6	0.0	Leaves may wilt and turn brown, and the plant may die.
10_7	0.5714285714285714	There are several species of flea beetles that damage vegetables and ornamentals.
10_8	0.1875	Among those that visit here are the tobacco flea beetle, the potato flea beetle and the eggplant flea beetle, which prefer nightshade-family plants such as eggplant and tomatoes.
10_9	0.42857142857142855	You may find flea beetles in your arugula, broccoli and corn, as well.
10_10	0.0	This pest is an accidental import, thought to have arrived in North America in the early 1900s, probably from Europe or Asia.
10_11	0.4	Adult flea beetles hibernate in the soil, then lay eggs in the soil or around the base of a plant.
10_12	0.0	In a week or so, larvae are feeding on plant roots before pupating and emerging as adults.
10_13	0.17647058823529413	Seemingly overnight, flea beetles recently visited our garden, peppering the leaves of two fuchsias with so many small holes that they left mere outlines of the foliage.
10_14	0.35714285714285715	If you are an organic gardener, you need quick hands to catch and squish these agile pests, as they bound away with the slightest hint of your approach.
10_15	0.0	They can slip underneath a leaf before you bat an eye.
10_16	0.0	Like other beetles, they are hard-bodied, and this, coupled with their acrobatic ability, makes it tough to easily nab them with a pesticide.
10_17	0.0	The pesticide needs to make good contact with the beetles, so you may be looking at more than one application.
10_18	0.0	Some of the chemicals commonly used around the garden target the pests.
10_19	0.16666666666666666	So do products that contain neem, a botanical pesticide.
10_20	0.25	Rotenone and pyrethrum products can work, too.
10_21	0.5555555555555556	In addition to eliminating as many of the enemy as possible with speedy fingers, the organic gardener has additional options: Use row covers to keep the pests off spring vegetables; repel them with garlic and hot pepper sprays; or capture them on white or yellow sticky traps.
