11_1	0.0	_ Sunrise at Sunnyside Farms is greeted by a ritual that startles the uninitiated.
11_2	0.19047619047619047	Workers advance upon windowless structures on wheels that are scattered around the 539 acres and lower the sides, releasing thousands of clucking chickens eager for a good day's work at what they do best: eating bugs.
11_3	0.3157894736842105	David Cole, venture capitalist, philanthropist and organic farmer, uses these coops on wheels _ chicken mobile units, they're called _ to move his chickens where the pecking is needed most.
11_4	0.05263157894736842	The mobile units are just one of many labor-savers he employs on the organic farm he started in 1995 in the middle of Rappahannock County, home to the very rich who have made their money elsewhere and to farmers who barely make a living.
11_5	0.09090909090909091	Like the cattle, sheep and goats that keep the pasture trimmed, the chickens take care of fertilizing it.
11_6	0.0	Like every aspect of his $11.5 million farm, the mobile units are state-of-the-art equipment intended to ensure the success of his experimental farm.
11_7	0.0	Money is no object, and money is not the only objective.
11_8	0.0	The farm is not a rich man's hobby.
11_9	0.0	It is a rich man's business, and Cole, who made his name as president of Internet services at America Online (and his money in a variety of other computer technology businesses), predicts confidently that Sunnyside will turn a profit by 2004.
11_10	0.0	In addition to its wagonloads of chickens, the farm has 424 head of Wagyu cattle (close relatives of the famous Japanese Kobe beef); 60 to 70 varieties of vegetables, herbs and flowers; and 8 to 10 varieties of berries, as well as pear, apple and cherry trees.
11_11	0.0	It is experimenting with more than 200 kinds of fruits and vegetables.
11_12	0.09090909090909091	But even more important to Cole is Sunnyside's role in promoting organic farming as economic savior.
11_13	0.0	By helping local growers profit in an era when independent farms are struggling, he hopes to create a model for reviving depressed agricultural areas around the country.
11_14	0.125	The idea of saving a region through organic farming might once have sounded outlandish.
11_15	0.0	But the demand for organic food nationwide is greater than the supply, and sales have increased by at least 20 percent annually for several years.
11_16	0.06666666666666667	Buyers looking for such food _ independently certified to be free of chemical pesticides, genetically engineered ingredients and antibiotics _ willingly pay a premium for it.
11_17	0.0	Cole, 47, calls his system network farming: a large central farm is the hub, with smaller nearby farms the spokes, their production marketed through the hub.
11_18	0.047619047619047616	Sunnyside's system is designed to show that diversified organic farming, with a mix of vegetables, fruits and animals, can be profitable while protecting the environment, not only from tract housing but also from the damage done to it by traditional farming methods.
11_19	0.6666666666666666	Such a system would be particularly useful in helping small organic farmers compete.
11_20	0.0	The concept is not new.
11_21	0.1111111111111111	Walnut Acres Organic Farms in Pennsylvania, which Cole just bought, operates in the same fashion.
11_22	0.0	But Sunnyside was set up to be an experimental demonstration farm.
11_23	0.0	``What he is doing is really rare,'' said Katherine DiMatteo, executive director of the Organic Trade Association.
11_24	0.0	``That he has the ability to have this diversity on his farm makes it unique.
11_25	0.0	It totally encompasses the breadth of on-farm innovation and research.
11_26	0.0	He is really taking new and old ideas and combining all that information into a full farm approach''.
11_27	0.0	So far three small farms have signed on with Sunnyside, and conversations with a dozen more farmers are under way.
11_28	0.05555555555555555	The farm pays to educate them in converting to organic techniques and gaining organic certification and gives them access to the expensive equipment needed to run an organic farm.
11_29	0.0	It also pays them 20 to 30 percent more than they would get if they were selling conventional food and, more important, gets their products to consumers.
11_30	0.0	``A weakness of a lot of farmers is marketing,'' said Brian Cramer, the gardener and orchard production manager at Sunnyside.
11_31	0.0	Selling at farmers' markets or farm stands, with no middlemen, ``is always preferable,'' he said, ``but some farmers don't want to do it''.
11_32	0.0	``Some don't have time to do it,'' he said, ``so they leave it to someone else, and they get taken advantage of''.
11_33	0.0	nn In the summer Sunnyside is opening a market in an 1835 building Cole is restoring in the center of the tiny town of Washington, Va.
11_34	0.0	, less than a block from his most prestigious customer, the Inn at Little Washington.
11_35	0.0	Its farmers' products will be sold there, at a farmers' market in Washington, D.C., and to restaurants, the Fresh Fields natural supermarket chain and an organic wholesaler who sells up and down the East Coast.
11_36	0.0	There will be more than 30 varieties of tomatoes, 15 different peppers and three dozen kinds of greens.
11_37	0.0	``Eventually we could have 8 or 10 spoke farms, and that could have a tremendous economic impact on the community,'' said Cole, who has restored the 1720 house on the farm, one of several places he lives with his wife of 30 years and the youngest of their four children.
11_38	0.0	(One son works for Sunnyside full time, another during the summer).
